Disposition (independent disposition subagent): Rejected.

Claim disposition: false at HEAD (53685bf). The finding asserts "Casting value as ZoteroSearchKey after checking Set<string>.has() provides no guarantee the value matches any literal member of the union type" — i.e. that the cast substitutes for runtime validation. The actual cast site is searchKey (src/utils/fuzzy.ts:257-260):

  function searchKey(value: string): ZoteroSearchKey {
    if (SEARCH_DOCUMENT_KEYS.has(value as ZoteroSearchKey)) return value as ZoteroSearchKey;
    throw new Error(`Unsupported Zotero search field: ${value}`);
  }

SEARCH_DOCUMENT_KEYS is typed Set<ZoteroSearchKey> and is populated (src/utils/fuzzy.ts:149-178) with exactly the union's literal members, derived from ZoteroSearchKey = Exclude<keyof ZoteroSearchDocument, 'item'> (src/utils/fuzzy.ts:147). The function THROWS on any value not in that set, so the cast is reached only for a value already proven to be a union member at runtime. This is a runtime guard that fails loud on mismatch — precisely the "crash at the boundary" pattern bespoke-software-policy mandates — not a cast standing in for validation.

The .has(value as ZoteroSearchKey) inner cast is only the argument-type widening required to query a Set<ZoteroSearchKey> with a string; it does not affect the membership truth value. The premise that "no guarantee the value matches a literal member" is contradicted by the throwing guard.

Policy basis: bespoke-software-policy Crash-at-the-Boundary (a guarded narrowing that throws on mismatch is the correct, fail-loud shape; this is NOT a banned type-erasure construct because the contract is enforced at runtime before the cast is trusted). Accepting the finding would import a redundant validation layer for a boundary that is already fail-loud.

No code change. Resolving as rejected.
